{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524472"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:05:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:05:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14001"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14001","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14001"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.1,0.8,0.06,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6650"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106995"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6650","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6650"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14001"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89459"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"107"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"4250"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13625"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13826"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16008"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106995","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106995"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 74-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of progressive right eye pain, swelling, and redness. He reports difficulty moving his right eye and blurred vision. He has a history of type 2 diabetes mellitus. His only regular medication is metformin. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell with a temperature of 38.5\u00b0C. His right eye shows marked periorbital swelling and erythema, with the eyelid almost completely closed (Image). There is proptosis of the right eye. Visual acuity in the right eye is reduced compared to the left.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute angle-closure glaucoma","Preseptal cellulitis","Orbital cellulitis","Endophthalmitis","Cavernous sinus thrombosis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation in this case is highly suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Eorbital cellulitis\u003C/strong\u003E. The key features supporting this diagnosis are the acute onset of periorbital swelling, erythema, proptosis, and impaired extraocular movements. The presence of fever and reduced visual acuity further support this diagnosis. Orbital cellulitis is a serious infection of the tissues posterior to the orbital septum, including the fat and muscle within the bony orbit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPreseptal cellulitis\u003C/strong\u003E involves infection of the eyelid and periorbital tissues anterior to the orbital septum. While it can cause eyelid swelling and redness, it typically does not affect eye movements or cause proptosis. The presence of these features in this case makes orbital cellulitis more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECavernous sinus thrombosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare but serious complication that can occur secondary to orbital cellulitis. It typically presents with bilateral eye involvement, severe headache, and cranial nerve palsies. While it should be considered as a potential complication, the unilateral presentation in this case makes orbital cellulitis the primary diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute angle-closure glaucoma\u003C/strong\u003E can cause a red, painful eye with reduced vision, but it does not typically cause the marked periorbital swelling and proptosis seen in this case. Additionally, the pupil would usually be mid-dilated and non-reactive in acute angle-closure glaucoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndophthalmitis\u003C/strong\u003E is an infection within the eye itself, typically following eye surgery or penetrating injury. While it can cause severe eye pain and vision loss, it does not usually result in the significant periorbital swelling and proptosis seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOrbital cellulitis is a medical emergency that requires prompt treatment with intravenous antibiotics. A CT scan of the orbits and sinuses is typically performed to confirm the diagnosis, assess the extent of the infection, and look for complications such as subperiosteal or orbital abscesses. The patient\u0027s diabetes is a risk factor for more severe infection and complications, emphasizing the need for urgent management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Orbital cellulitis is characterized by eyelid swelling, erythema, proptosis, and impaired extraocular movements.","Orbital cellulitis is a medical emergency that requires prompt treatment with intravenous antibiotics.","CT scan is the imaging modality of choice to confirm the diagnosis and assess for complications of orbital cellulitis."],"references":["Clinical Practice Guideline, Preseptal and Orbital Cellulitis. In: Royal Eye and Ear Hospital [Online]. Available at: https://eyeandear.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/Preseptal-and-Orbital-Cellulitis-Clinical-Practice-Guideline.pdf","Yadalla D, Jayagayathri R, Padmanaban K, Ramasamy R, Rammohan R, Nisar SP, Rangarajan V, Menon V. Bacterial orbital cellulitis - A review. Indian J Ophthalmol. 2023 Jul;71(7):2687-2693. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC10491050/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89459"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14001"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20912"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20912","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20912"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8g2xGmkhyJM5Q69g3GXdqMNv6MFZDl.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8g2xGmkhyJM5Q69g3GXdqMNv6MFZDl.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89459","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89459"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-24T16:48:22+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-24T16:48:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6650"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106995"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"20","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/20"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4c","name":"Plastic Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":